<div id="about-those-224000-jobs" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#about-those-224000-jobs">3:15 P.M.</a></span> <strong>About Those 224,000 Jobs&#8230;</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Members of Congress and other critics of the new E.P.A. regulations have been citing three main talking points in the immediate reaction to the announcement of the rules: </p>
<blockquote class="twitter-tweet tw-hide-thread"><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The @EPA&#8217;s proposed rules will destroy jobs and hurt our economy. //t.co/coHKQDgrpG //t.co/tN9oa8Tyb8</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">â <a href="https://www.twitter.com/RepSteveChabot">Steve Chabot (@RepSteveChabot)</a> <a href="https://www.twitter.com/RepSteveChabot/status/473499818355331072" data-datetime="2014-06-02T16:22:08+00:00">2 Jun 14</a><script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" id="platform_twitter_js" charset="utf-8"></script></p>
</blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">These numbers come from a <a href="//www.energyxxi.org/epa-regs">71-page study released on Wednesday</a> by the United States Chamber of Commerce, called âAssessing the Impact of Potential New Carbon Regulations in the United States.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The study was released before the regulations were announced, based on <a href="//www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-fi-climate-change-impact-chamber-commerce-study-20140528-story.html">an assumed 42 percent reduction in greenhouse-gas emissions</a> by 2030 from 2005 levels.  In the regulations announced today, however, President Obama and the E.P.A. are proposing to cut carbon pollution from the nationâs power plants 30 percent from 2005 levels by 2030.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The E.P.A., last week, <a href="//blog.epa.gov/epaconnect/2014/05/setting-the-record-straight-on-the-chamber-of-commerces-report/ ">issued its own rebuttal</a>, arguing that âthere are some major gaps in the numbers touted by the Chamber.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>NICK CORASANITI</em></p>
</div></div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="coal-state-democrats-cool-to-climate-plan" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#coal-state-democrats-cool-to-climate-plan">2:07 p.m.</a></span> <strong>Coal State Democrats Bristle at Climate Plan</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There are Democrats in coal country and many of them are not pleased with President Obama&#8217;s plan to curb carbon emissions. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//coalblue.org/leaders/">CoalBlue</a>, a group of Democratic lawmakers from coal states, has come out against the proposal, calling it &#8220;flawed and imprudent.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The group says that the Obama administration is marginalizing coal when it should be working to develop sustainable coal technologies. It also argues that a strategy that raises energy costs will not be accepted in developing countries, making the plan counterproductive at solving a global problem.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;While raising the cost of coal and other carbon-rich fuels in the United States will reduce the domestic consumption of such fuels, higher energy costs will also lead to the loss and transfer of economic activity â and jobs â from the United States to nations with more carbon-intense economies,&#8221; CoalBlue said in a statement. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The group says that the United States should instead be investing in low-carbon energy technology rather than clamping down on coal.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>ALAN RAPPEPORT</em></p>
</div></div>
