<div id="in-kentucky-coal-is-more-powerful-than-party" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#in-kentucky-coal-is-more-powerful-than-party">2:03 p.m.</a></span> <strong>In Kentucky, Coal is More Powerful Than Party</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Kentucky generates more than 90 percent of its power from coal and is third in the country in coal production. The Bluegrass State is the heart of Coal Country. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This might explain why Alison Lundergan Grimes, the Democratic challenger to Senator Mitch McConnell who has been anxious to parry with Mr. McConnell over nearly every issue, is aligning herself with her opponent on the Environmental Protection Agency&#8217;s carbon emissions rule.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Breaking with President Obama and most Democrats, Ms. Grimes released a statement on Monday vowing to fight the new regulations.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âPresident Obamaâs new E.P.A. rule is more proof that Washington isnât working for Kentucky,â <a href="//alisonforkentucky.com/news/grimes-statement-on-the-epas-new-overreaching-regulations/">Ms. Grimes said</a>. âCoal keeps the lights on in the Commonwealth, providing a way for thousands of Kentuckians to put food on their tables.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Earlier, Mr. McConnell released <a href="//www.mcconnell.senate.gov/public/index.cfm?p=PressReleases&#038;ContentRecord_id=321eda5a-8bcb-49c3-a55e-1f8e96d6f350&#038;ContentType_id=c19bc7a5-2bb9-4a73-b2ab-3c1b5191a72b&#038;Group_id=0fd6ddca-6a05-4b26-8710-a0b7b59a8f1f">a blistering condemnation</a> of the rules, saying they were âa dagger in the heart of the American middle class.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>NICK CORASANITI</em></p>
</div></div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="boehner-hits-obama-on-2008-promise" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#boehner-hits-obama-on-2008-promise">12:04 P.M.</a></span> <strong>Boehner Hits Obama on 2008 Promise</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Republicans are using President Obama&#8217;s new climate initiative as an &#8220;I told you so&#8221; moment.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Opponents of the plan have surfaced <a href="//www.speaker.gov/video/promise-made-promise-kept-electricity-rates-skyrocket">a video clip</a> that was used against Mr. Obama during his 2008 and 2012 campaigns. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Speaker John A. Boehner tweeted footage of an interview with The San Francisco Chronicle from January 2008, when Mr. Obama, then a senator, said &#8220;under my plan of a cap-and-trade system, electricity rates would necessarily skyrocket.&#8221; Mr. Obama said that was because by proposing to cap greenhouse gasses, coal power plants would have to retrofit their operations and pass those costs on to consumers. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The remarks became stump speech fodder for Senator John McCain and former Gov. Mitt Romney in their successive contests against Mr. Obama. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The E.P.A. does not deny that its proposal would raise average retail electricity prices nationwide in 2020 and 2030, but it claims that average monthly bills would decline because greater &#8220;efficiency&#8221; would mean consumers would use less electricity.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>ALAN RAPPEPORT</em></p>
</div></div>
