<div id="consumer-group-says-utility-rates-will-drop" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#consumer-group-says-utility-rates-will-drop">12:00 P.M.</a></span> <strong>Consumer Group Says Utility Rates Will Drop</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Public Citizen, the consumer advocacy group founded by Ralph Nader, disputed claims that the crackdown on carbon emissions from power plants would cause electric bills to rise.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âConsumers desperately need aggressive action to avert catastrophic climate change,â the groupâs president, Robert Weissman, <a href="//www.citizen.org/pressroom/pressroomredirect.cfm?ID=4205">said in a statement</a>. âWe celebrate todayâs announced E.P.A. rules as an important step forward, even as we note that the science demands much more aggressive action be taken.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Weissman cited <a href="//www.citizen.org/documents/consumer-case-for-carbon-standard-june-2014.pdf">an internal study</a> by the group that found that coal was âartificially cheapâ because it did not factor in the âfull health, environmental and carbon costs for coal.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After those costs are included, âconsumers may well see lower electricity bills,â Mr. Weissman said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>DAVID S. JOACHIM</em></p>
