<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="coal-advocacy-responds" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#coal-advocacy-responds">11:12 A.M.</a></span> <strong>Coal Advocacy Group Responds</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Obama administrationâs plan takes direct aim at the nationâs 600 coal-fired power plants, collectively the largest source of carbon pollution in the United States â and, not incidentally, the biggest source of electric power generation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The American Coalition for Clean Coal Electricity came out swinging this morning, calling President Obamaâs plan âcostly,â âmisguidedâ and âdevastatingâ to the economy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIf these rules are allowed to go into effect, the administration for all intents and purposes is creating Americaâs next energy crisis,â Mike Duncan, the groupâs president and a former chairman of the Republican National Committee, said in a <a href="//www.americaspower.org/accce-initial-review-111d-epa-carbon-emissions-rule-misses-mark">statement</a>. âThese guidelines represent a complete disregard for our countryâs most vital fuel sources, like American coal, which provides nearly 40 percent of Americaâs power, reliably and affordably,â he added.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Duncan warned of rolling blackouts and higher utility bills, particularly for lower-income Americans.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âSadly, E.P.A.âs proposed regulations put Americaâs low- and middle-income families most at risk of paying disproportionately more for energy,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>DAVID S. JOACHIM</em></p>
</div></div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="mccain-and-climate-change-a-history" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#mccain-and-climate-change-a-history">11:07 A.M.</a></span> <strong>McCain and Climate Change: A History</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Republican lawmakers can be counted on to chastise President Obama for his plan to cut carbon pollution from the nationâs power plants substantially by 2030. But six years ago, Republicans were backing a proposal by their front-runner and eventual nominee for president, Senator John McCain of Arizona, for a similar plan.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As Mr. McCain sought to distance himself from the deeply unpopular Bush administration, he called for a mandatory limit on greenhouse gas emissions in the United States to combat climate change, as <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2008/05/13/us/politics/13mccain.html?_r=0">The New York Times reported</a> at the time.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.vox.com/2014/6/2/5770506/remember-when-the-gop-believed-in-climate-change">Ezra Klein of Vox</a> pointed out this morning that Mr. McCainâs plan was even more aggressive than Mr. Obamaâs, aiming to cut emissions by at least 60 percent below 1990 levels by 2050. The Republican Party, including Mr. McCain&#8217;s Tea Party-inspired running mate, Gov. Sarah Palin of Alaska, endorsed that plan.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At the time, Mr. Obama and Hillary Rodham Clinton, still locked in a close race for the Democratic presidential nomination, were proposing an 80 percent cut in the same time frame. Now, as president, Mr. Obama wants to cut emissions by 30 percent from 2005 levels by 2030.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>DAVID S. JOACHIM</em></p>
</div></div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="republican-leaders-slam-climate-plan" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#republican-leaders-slam-climate-plan">11:07 A.M.</a></span> <strong>Republican Leaders Criticize Climate Plan</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Opposition to the Obama administration&#8217;s climate plan was pouring in even before the proposal was unveiled. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Republican leadership did not hesitate to condemn the proposal. Senator Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, the minority leader, called the proposal a &#8220;dagger in the heart of the American middle class, and to representative democracy itself.&#8221; He said that the proposal to cut carbon emissions would mean higher costs, fewer jobs and a less reliable energy grid.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Meanwhile, the House speaker, John A. Boehner of Ohio, used equally forceful rhetoric, calling the plan a &#8220;sucker punch&#8221; to American families by causing a surge in electricity bills.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>ALAN RAPPEPORT</em></p>
